putantes faciant in dolore. As the MS

reading thus yields a good sense it does not seem well to depart from it. lzoc after haec omnia... is hardly what we should expect from Cicero. Wes. pro- posed haec and the confusion between lzoc and llaec in Mss is very common. Ml. thinks hoc no more to be changed into haec than utraque in re into utrisque in rebus in Lael. 17, 64 ex. where in bonis rebus aut in malis preceded. Hei., followed by T.S.‚ reads declaratur haec. For eo supplied in thought before quod Hei. compares Off. i 18, 61 ‘declaratur autem studium bellicae gloriae, quod statuas quoque uidemus ornatu fere mili- tari? Or. Kl. Bai. and Sff. read declarat icoc, Bai. noting that hoc is to be taken as nom. and that the subj. acc. to fieri is llaec omnia.
